nternational trade fair projects -- tChinese companies at European trade fairs -- tWhy China needs more Professional Congress Organisers (PCOs) -- tHow to organise successful meetings in China -- tThe evolution of the Chinese events market – An agency perspective -- tA City Brand Personality Model for international event marketing: An empirical research across multiple cultures -- tEducation for China’s event industry -- tFit for the future? Some thoughts on event education in a changing world -- tThe event industry and its human resources: A view based on the characteristics of the industry -- tEducation of event management in Germany and China: A comparison -- tWhere do they want to go? Expectations of Chinese talents from their future employer -- tLearning style of Chinese event management students -- tLecturing key competencies in China and the challenge of transnational education -- tAuthors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aChina’s event market is full of dynamic and exciting developments, innovation, new players and novel ideas, but at the same time of certain shortcomings. This new and huge market is drawing increasing attention from the event industry worldwide. The aim of this handbook is to analyse the Chinese event market, reflect on emerging trends, scrutinise the key players and identify the implica-tions for the education of future professionals in this industry. This handbook is the first of its kind on the Chinese event market written in English. It is a collection of 27articles written by 39 authors from China, Germany, Malaysia, South Africa, the United Kingdom and the United States. The contributions embrace a mix of theoretical and practical reflections, written by academics/lecturers and practitioners alike. The focus lies on business events, such as trade fairs, conventions and corporate events. Some very specifically describe a certain trend or development; others focus on overall trends. The handbook is divided into four chapters. Following an introductory chapter on the event market, the second chapter focuses on the event market in China from a global perspective. The third chapter reflects on management aspects in China’s event industry. The fourth and final chapter addresses the issue of educating professionals for the event industry.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aSpecial events industryxChinaxChina. 0aSpecial events industryzChina. 0aSpecial eventsxMarketingxChina. 0aSpecial eventszChinaxMarketing. 0aSpecial eventsz ChinaxMarketing. 4aChina Exhibition. 4aTrade Fair. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Industries / Hospitality, Travel & Tourism.2bisacsh1 aCai, Meng, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChen, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChen, Xianjin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChen, Zeyan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDams, Colja M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDing, Ye, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDing, Yi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDing, Yi, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDu, Jiayi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrey, Andreas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaida, Hans-Jürgen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGao, Frankie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGervers, Susanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGray, Clare, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabula